					<description><![CDATA[“Beyond Mind” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, obsidian, tourmaline, and mixed media, 27 x 26 x 13 inches. Photo by Luc Demers. All images © Lauren Fensterstock, shared with permission When a massive star dies, it collapses with an enormous explosion that produces a supernova. In some cases, the remains become a black hole, the [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>
<div id="attachment_246201" style="width: 1804px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246201" class="wp-image-246201 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/5-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="a round sculpture covered in a glimmering black mosaic with sharp clear crystals jutting out near the bottom right along with another bulbous shape" width="1794" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/5-Fensterstock.jpg 1794w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/5-Fensterstock-640x685.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/5-Fensterstock-960x1027.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/5-Fensterstock-1435x1536.jpg 1435w" sizes="(max-width: 1794px) 100vw, 1794px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246201" class="wp-caption-text">“Beyond Mind” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, obsidian, tourmaline, and mixed media, 27 x 26 x 13 inches. Photo by Luc Demers. All images © Lauren Fensterstock, shared with permission</p>
</div>
<p>When a massive star dies, it collapses with an enormous explosion that produces a supernova. In some cases, the remains become a black hole, the enigmatic phenomenon that traps everything it comes into contact with—even light itself.</p>
<p>The life cycle of stars informs the most recent works by artist <a href="https://laurenfensterstock.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Lauren Fensterstock</a>, who applies the principles of such stellar transformations to human interaction and connection. From her studio in Portland, Maine, she creates dense mosaics of fragmented crystals and stones including quartz, obsidian, and tourmaline that glimmer when hit by light and form shadowy areas of intrigue when not.</p>
<p>Cloaking sculptures and large-scale installations, Fensterstock’s dazzling compositions evoke natural forms like flowers, stars, and clouds and speak to cosmic and terrestrial entanglement. “I have to admit that I agonize over the placement of every single (piece),” the artist shares. “There are days where it flows together like a magical puzzle and other days where I place, rip out, and redo a square inch of surface again and again for hours. Even amidst a huge mass of material, every moment has to have that feeling of effortless perfection.”</p>
<p> </p>
<div id="attachment_246202" style="width: 1248px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246202" class="wp-image-246202 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/10-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="a massive black orb with spikes and glimmering crystals hangs from the ceiling over a bed of black fringe" width="1238" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/10-Fensterstock.jpg 1238w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/10-Fensterstock-640x993.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/10-Fensterstock-960x1489.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/10-Fensterstock-990x1536.jpg 990w" sizes="(max-width: 1238px) 100vw, 1238px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246202" class="wp-caption-text">“The totality of time lusters the dusk” (2020), mixed media, installation at The Renwick Gallery of the Smithsonian American Art Museum. Photo by Ron Blunt</p>
</div>
<p>The gems are sometimes firmly embedded within the surface and at others, appear to explode outward in an energetic eruption. Celestial implosions are apt metaphors for transformation, the artist says, and “pairs of stars speak to the complexities of personal connections… In the newest work—which explores vast sky maps filled with multiple constellations—I attempt to move beyond a single star or an isolated self to show the entanglement of the cosmic whole.”</p>
<p>While beautiful on their own, the precious materials explore broader themes in aggregate.  Just as astrology uses constellations and cosmic machinations to offer insight and meaning into the unknown, Fensterstock’s jeweled sculptures chart relationships between the individual and the universe to draw closer to the divine.</p>
<p>The artist is currently working toward a solo show opening this fall at <a href="https://www.claireoliver.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Claire Oliver Gallery</a> in Harlem. Inspired by her daily meditation practice, she’ll present elaborately mapped creations of lotuses, black holes, fallen stars, and a bow and arrow that appear as offerings to the universe. In addition to that exhibition, the artist is showing in May at the <a href="https://shelburnemuseum.org/exhibition/new-england-strange-states/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Shelburne Museum</a> and will attend <a href="https://civitella.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">a residency</a> in Italy this September, to work on a book about entanglement and artist muses. Find more about those projects and her multi-faceted practice on <a href="https://laurenfensterstock.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">her website</a> and <a href="https://www.instagram.com/laurenfensterstock/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Instagram</a>.</p>
<p> </p>
<div id="attachment_246200" style="width: 1452px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246200" class="wp-image-246200 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/4-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="a detail image of mosaic crystals with a cluster of a spiky crystals" width="1442" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/4-Fensterstock.jpg 1442w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/4-Fensterstock-640x852.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/4-Fensterstock-960x1278.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/4-Fensterstock-1154x1536.jpg 1154w" sizes="(max-width: 1442px) 100vw, 1442px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246200" class="wp-caption-text">Detail of “Dwelling” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, and mixed media, 18 x 16 x 13 inches. Photo by Luc Demers</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246214" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246214" class="wp-image-246214 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fenterstock.jpg" alt="left: a black floral sculpture covered in mosaic tiles and glimmering crystals. right: right: a silver floral sculpture covered in mosaic tiles and glimmering crystals. " width="1920" height="1039" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fenterstock.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fenterstock-640x346.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fenterstock-960x520.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/fenterstock-1536x831.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246214" class="wp-caption-text">Left: “The Undiluted” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, obsidian, tourmaline, and mixed media. Photo by Luc Demers. Right: “The Unhurt” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, and mixed media, 22 x 27 x 14 inches. Photo by Luc Demers</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246203" style="width: 1284px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246203" class="wp-image-246203 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/11-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="string of black beads dangle from black cloud like sculptures covered in beads, mosaic, and crystals" width="1274" height="1920" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/11-Fensterstock.jpg 1274w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/11-Fensterstock-640x965.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/11-Fensterstock-960x1447.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/11-Fensterstock-1019x1536.jpg 1019w" sizes="(max-width: 1274px) 100vw, 1274px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246203" class="wp-caption-text">“The totality of time lusters the dusk” (2020), mixed media, installation at The Renwick Gallery of the Smithsonian American Art Museum. Photo by Ron Blunt</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246199" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246199" class="wp-image-246199 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/2-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="left: a floral sculpture with numerous leaves all covered in glimerring stones and crystals. right: a floral wall sculpture with black glimmering stones in the center and silver petals" width="1920" height="1038" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/2-Fensterstock.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/2-Fensterstock-640x346.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/2-Fensterstock-960x519.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/2-Fensterstock-1536x830.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246199" class="wp-caption-text">Left: “The Many” (2023), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, and mixed media, 38 x 38 x 10 inches. Image courtesy of Claire Oliver Gallery. Right: “Heart of Negation” (2022), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, and mixed media, 54 × 54 × 14 inches</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246205" style="width: 2010px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246205" class="wp-image-246205 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/16.-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="a half-orb sculpture with a glimmering black inside and sharp clear crystals around the outside" width="2000" height="1923" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/16.-Fensterstock.jpg 2000w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/16.-Fensterstock-640x615.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/16.-Fensterstock-960x923.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/16.-Fensterstock-1536x1477.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 2000px) 100vw, 2000px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246205" class="wp-caption-text">“Eclipse” (2022), vintage crystal, glass, quartz, obsidian, tourmaline, and mixed media. Photo by Luc Demers</p>
</div>
<div id="attachment_246206" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption alignnone"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-246206" class="wp-image-246206 size-full" src="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/19-Fensterstock.jpg" alt="three black cabinets on a wall with black objects and large growths overwhelming the shelves" width="1920" height="962" srcset="https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/19-Fensterstock.jpg 1920w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/19-Fensterstock-640x321.jpg 640w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/19-Fensterstock-960x481.jpg 960w, https://www.thisiscolossal.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/04/19-Fensterstock-1536x770.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 1920px) 100vw, 1920px"></p>
<p id="caption-attachment-246206" class="wp-caption-text">“The Order of Things” (2016), shells and mixed media</p>
</div>
